	<div class="pagecontent">
		<h2 id="activelearning">Active Learning</h2>
		<p>Research shows that learning improves when students are actively participating, applying, and synthesizing new skills and concepts, and that learning tends to suffer when students are passive, bored, or otherwise disengaged. How can we engage students in active learning? Research shows that engaged students earn higher grades, perform better on tests, can set and meet personal goals, persist on tasks, expect success, and value educational outcomes.</p>
		<img src="images/60-40-ratio.png" alt="ratio">

		<p>Start class with students responding to a short prompt (write, diagram, discuss with a partner).</p>
		<p>Pause every 10 minutes of lecture for short activities (explore a concept, practice a skill) for students to apply/synthesize learning, and check for understanding (reteach if necessary).</p>
		<p>Assign challenges to small groups for cooperative learning; count-off to group and move students around room; give clear directions; let the students lead.</p>
		<p>Use images and graphics to make your teaching visible, memorable, and to clarify ideas.</p>
		<p>Use questioning strategies and checks for understanding that make all students think and answer.</p>
		<p>Instead of whole-class discussions, use techniques like Turn-and-Talk, or Write-Share.</p>
		<p>Time box lesson activities to create a sense of urgency and focus.
		Use examples that are relevant to students’ lives and goals. Make it matter to them.</p>
		<p>Ask extension questions following student responses: Why do you think that? How do you know this? Can you tell me more? What questions do you still have?</p>
		<p>End class with an Exit Task – a quick student survey about the lesson’s key takeaways, their level of confidence or remaining challenges with the new skills or concepts.</p>

		
