		<h2 id="studentengagement">Student Engagement</h2>
		<h3>Dodgeball as a Talking Stick</h3>
		<p>Keep a dodgeball in the front of the room to call on students when answering questions. You throw, they catch, then they answer the question.  If they don’t know the answer or another student wanted to add on, they can throw the ball to that student.  You can call names and toss or ask a “how many answers can we think of for this question” and popcorn the ball around the room.</p>
		<h3>Music Break</h3>
		<p>There’s nothing wrong with a quick auditory break!  By putting on a song, we give the class a timed break and provide a bit of relief to those musically inclined. Remember those multiple intelligences?</p>
		<h3>Seventh Inning Stretch</h3>
		<p>When students sit for long periods of time, their muscles tense & they need to stretch out.  Lead some stretches to optimize focus & attention, and release pent-up energy so students can focus going forward.  You can offer students a go-to “seventh-inning stretch” which is a quick exercise that you lead in the class, possibly during the mid-afternoon slump.</p>
